        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer106380785" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2256582830335789143">It seems wrong and somewhat sad that my favorite Gaiman book is not one of his many heralded novels, but a collection of short stories. Mind you, <i>Fragile Things</i> is a great collection of short stories! <br/><br/>Some of the content herein is much more &quot;adult&quot; than a good deal of his other work, which can tend towards the childlike and fanciful. Don&apos;t get me wrong, I enjoy the fantastical stuff with its focus on the magic of youth and mystery of the unknown. But I think I prefer his short story work because</span>
  <span id="freeText2256582830335789143" style="display:none">It seems wrong and somewhat sad that my favorite Gaiman book is not one of his many heralded novels, but a collection of short stories. Mind you, <i>Fragile Things</i> is a great collection of short stories! <br /><br />Some of the content herein is much more "adult" than a good deal of his other work, which can tend towards the childlike and fanciful. Don't get me wrong, I enjoy the fantastical stuff with its focus on the magic of youth and mystery of the unknown. But I think I prefer his short story work because it seems more well-crafted and honed to a higher perfection than some of his full length novels, which feel a bit loose at times. <br /><br />In summation, here is my newspaper book review title for this: "Gaiman's <i>Fragile Things</i> Is Strong Stuff"....*shakes head*....horrible...horrible.</span>
